g.text: All LEDs used are CHANZON brand, 5 mm packages. Each has a forward voltage of 2 V and a forward current of 20 mA.

g.desc: All LEDs used are CHANZON brand, 5 mm packages. Each has a forward voltage of 2 V and a forward current of 20 mA.

g.text: To calculate the current limiting resistor value at maximum battery voltage: V = IR =(4.2 V - 2 V) = (20 mA)R -> R = 110 ohms.

g.desc: To calculate the current limiting resistor value at maximum battery voltage: V = IR =(4.2 V - 2 V) = (20 mA)R -> R = 110 ohms.

g.text: To account for resistor tolerances, I rounded up to the next standard value of 120 ohms. Calculating the current through the

g.desc: To account for resistor tolerances, I rounded up to the next standard value of 120 ohms. Calculating the current through the

g.text: LEDs at minimum battery voltage with this resistor gives: 2.5 - 2 V = I(120 ohms) -> I = 4.17 mA.

g.desc: LEDs at minimum battery voltage with this resistor gives: 2.5 - 2 V = I(120 ohms) -> I = 4.17 mA.

g.text: I am running each of the 555 timers in astable mode. To determine timing, 3 values need to be chosen: Ra, Rb, and C.

g.desc: I am running each of the 555 timers in astable mode. To determine timing, 3 values need to be chosen: Ra, Rb, and C.

g.text: It is generally recommended to choose a value for Ra that is 10% of Rb's value, so I picked standard values of 7.5 kohms for Ra

g.desc: It is generally recommended to choose a value for Ra that is 10% of Rb's value, so I picked standard values of 7.5 kohms for Ra

g.text: and 75 kohms for Rb. This gives an adequate duty cycle as follows: D = Rb/(Ra + 2Rb)*100 = 47.62%.

g.desc: and 75 kohms for Rb. This gives an adequate duty cycle as follows: D = Rb/(Ra + 2Rb)*100 = 47.62%.

g.text: I wanted to aim for a frequency of about 1 Hz for each timer so that the LEDs are on for about 0.5 seconds. Choosing a

g.desc: I wanted to aim for a frequency of about 1 Hz for each timer so that the LEDs are on for about 0.5 seconds. Choosing a

g.text: standard C value of 10 uF gives the following frequency: f = 1.44/[(Ra + 2Rb)C] = 1.44/[(7500 + (2*75000))*10^-5] = 0.914 Hz.

g.desc: standard C value of 10 uF gives the following frequency: f = 1.44/[(Ra + 2Rb)C] = 1.44/[(7500 + (2*75000))*10^-5] = 0.914 Hz.
